<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 15 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 15 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Siladzic Demands `Appropriate Measures' </H4>

<F P=102> LD1704150894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1704150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] We have just learned that Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime 
Minister Haris Silajdzic has sent a letter to the UN Security 
Council [UNSC] chairman. The letter reads: 
  You are aware that the aggressor has been attacking the 
protected zone of Gorazde for 20 days now, using troops and 
military equipment brought from Serbia and Montenegro. The 
aggressor's forces have occupied a large part of the protected 
zone and destroyed and burned down 21 villages around Gorazde. 
Some 230 people have been killed and 800 wounded in the town 
center. Civilian facilities in the centre of Gorazde are being 
destroyed with all available weapons. Tens of thousands of 
people are facing death from shooting or starvation, the letter 
says. 
  It is a fact that the United Nations and its representatives 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina did not use their mandate and powers 
granted to them by UNSC resolutions 824 and 836. As a 
consequence the population which -- through the arms embargo -- 
has been denied the right to self-defense has been left without 
any protection. We therefore consider those who make decisions 
within the UN as being responsible for what has happened, the 
letter says. 
  We demand that the UNSC urgently take appropriate measures 
in 
keeping with Article 7 of the UN Charter, which means to use 
force to stop the attacks by Serb aggressor's forces against 
Gorazde. We repeat that this is an aggression by Serbia and 
Montenegro against the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, which has 
been going on for two years. We demand the urgent establishment 
of an exclusion zone around Gorazde, from which the aggressor's 
troops and military equipment must withdraw. 
  Mr. President, we are talking about tens of thousands of 
civilians who, together with the rest of the world, expect that 
the peace-keeping forces will fulfill their duty, the letter 
says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

