Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 16 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 16 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Krajisnik Meets Churkin in Pale </H4>

<F P=102> AU1604205694 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1604205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Momcilo Krajisnik, chairman of the Srpska republic 
assembly, in Pale today held long talks with Russian special 
envoy Vitaliy Churkin. Reporter Mirjana Kursmuk talked to 
Chairman Krajisnik. 
  [Begin recording] [Kursmuk] Today you were supposed to meet 
with the UN secretary general's special envoy Yasushi Akashi. 
However, the meeting never took place. Can you tell us what 
really happened? 
  [Krajisnik] Well, we received information that Mr. Akashi 
and Mr. Churkin wished to meet with us. The first meeting was 
set for 1130, and later for 1340. Only Mr. Churkin arrived, and 
not Mr. Akashi. He told us that unforeseen difficulties had 
arisen, and that Mr. Churkin [as heard] was called to return to 
Sarajevo, so that he actually turned back when he was already on 
his way and went back to Sarajevo [sentence as heard]. We 
spent almost the entire day in talks with Mr. Churkin, trying to 
find a solution, because the situation was very dramatic around 
Gorazde itself and on the international level because there was 
constant danger of another air attack. There were several 
unconfirmed reports that our tank had entered the town of 
Gorazde, that it was firing at Gorazde, and that this would be 
reason for a military intervention. Not only support for the UN 
Protection Force in the form of a military strike [as heard], 
but a military intervention which would mean a general attack. 
We managed to dispel this dilemma through constant contact with 
our General Staff and our commanders on the ground, because our 
tank was not in that position. We nevertheless issued orders 
that fire was not to be opened on the town itself. After that, 
pressure eased, and dilemmas regarding our attacks on Gorazde 
were dispelled. We are still in the midst of talks, because 
there is pressure for Serbs to withdraw away from Gorazde, but 
the Serbs cannot withdraw. Moreover, they did not advance in 
the course of the day. That was inaccurate information launched 
by the Muslims. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

