<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Izetbegovic Blames Butrus-Ghali </H4>

<F P=102> LD1704164894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1600 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1704164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the Presidency of 
the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, has sent a letter to UN 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali about the [word indistinct] 
situation in Gorazde. The letter reads: 
  The news I have received from Gorazde says that the town is 
in agony. For 20 days Karadzic's Serbs and units of the 
Yugoslav army have been attacking the town -- besieged for 10 
months -- with unabated intensity. The strange game, in which 
the obvious things are not seen, loud voices are not heard, and 
mechanisms have become impotent, has also been going on for 20 
days. The so-called protected zone has become the most unsafe 
area in the world. 
  The organization which you head proclaimed the free 
territory 
of Gorazde a UN-protected area almost a year ago. Security 
Council resolutions 824 and 836 refer to this protected zone, 
but they have remained only empty phrases. Neither you nor your 
personnel have done anything, or hardly anything, to use the 
mandate of all those resolutions in order to protect the people 
of Gorazde and the credibility of the United Nations. The 
result is obviously tragic. 
  Mr. Secretary General, my people hold you responsible for 
this situation. This [words indistinct] is bleeding, and there 
is not much room for diplomatic hesitation. If Gorazde falls, I 
think that the feeling of moral responsibility would command you 
to leave the post of UN secretary general. This is the least 
you can do for this (?suffering) people whose two years of 
suffering the world has watched with so much indifference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8756 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu074_i_94029" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Krajisnik Says Muslims Downed Plane </H4>

<F P=102> LD1704172294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1712 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 17 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb 
Parliamentary Speaker Momcilo Krajisnik said on Sunday Serbs 
insisted that a Gorazde ceasefire must be part of a general 
ceasefire for all of Bosnia-Herzegovina and must entail the 
lifting of U.N. sanctions against Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro). 
  Speaking for the local radio in Kragujevac, Serbia, 
Krajisnik 
said international mediators were insisting on a separate 
solution for the Moslem enclave of Gorazde in eastern Bosnia, 
but the Serb side would not agree to any partial arrangements 
but only to a general cessation of hostilities in all of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Krajisnik said that Russian envoy Vitaliy Churkin and U.N. 
special envoy Yasushi Akashi had informed the Serb side that the 
Moslems wished to open talks on the problem, which was probably 
a serious offer. He added however that similar agreements 
reached in the past had not been honoured. 
  Commenting on the downing of a British NATO plane over 
Gorazde, Krajisnik said: "The Serbs meant to down (NATO) planes 
only if they flew over their territory" which was not the case 
on Saturday, which means that the Serbs had not fired fire at 
the British plane which any investigation would show [sentence 
as received]. 
  The British aircraft fell in Moslem-controlled territory. 
  The Bosnian Serb command said it had intercepted a message 
from the Moslems in Gorazde to the Moslem command in Sarajevo 
saying that they had downed the plane and were holding the pilot 
who had bailed out. 
  The Bosnian Serb command has repeatedly warned that the 
Moslems in Gorazde, frustrated by the imminent defeat of their 
late March offensive on the surrounding Serb territories, might 
go so far as to down NATO planes to provoke a NATO military 
intervention against Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

