<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Cease-Fire Accord Signed </H4>

<F P=102> LD1704174294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1732 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 17 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic said on Sunday an immediate ceasefire for the 
Gorazde area had been agreed upon during his talks with U.N. 
special envoy Yasushi Akashi. 
  "We have agreed on the separation of forces as much as 
possible, maximum restraint from actions and provocations and, 
finally, the maximum effort in the humanitarian sphere," said 
Karadzic after talks with Akashi in Pale, the political and 
military centre of the Bosnian Serb republic. 
  He said U.N. helicopters would evacuate the wounded from 
Gorazde on Monday morning and added: "If we succeed in 
implementing the ceasefire and the separation of forces, we can 
say we are approaching peace in Gorazde." 
  Fighting in the Gorazde area escalated in late March, when 
about 10,000 Moslems from Gorazde -- a U.N.-designated "safe 
haven" which should have been demilitarized last spring -- 
mounted a powerful offensive on the surrounding Serb 
territories. The Serbs responded by launching a 
counteroffensive. 
  When the Moslems were all but defeated, the U.N. stepped in 
and ordered NATO air strikes against Bosnian Serb positions 
around Gorazde, after which the Serbs suspended all relations 
with the U.N. Protection Force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

