<H3> <TI>   Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Events in Gorazde -- 17 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Karadzic, Akashi Comment on Truce </H4>

<F P=102> AU1704184994 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1704184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Mirjana Kusmuk report from Pale] </F>
  [Text] [Begin recording] [Kusmuk] The meeting between the 
political leadership of the Srpska republic on one side, and UN 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali's special envoy Yasushi Akashi 
and Russian envoy for former Yugoslavia Vitaliy Churkin on the 
other side, ended in Pale today at 1700 [1500 GMT]. After the 
meeting, president of the Srpska republic Radovan Karadzic said: 
  [Karadzic] I wish to say that today's talks were long. 
Considering the crisis that we are gradually overcoming, it is 
not surprising that they were long and difficult, but in any 
case we have made some progress in overcoming the crisis, 
particularly regarding our relations with the United Nations and 
the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR]. Today we achieved certain 
progress as regards the position of UNPROFOR members on our 
territory. [Words indistinct] that it has still not reached all 
the headquarters, but it will reach them in any case. As far as 
Gorazde is concerned, the situation is much more complex and 
very difficult to resolve. We have agreed to order an immediate 
cease-fire, a certain disengagement of forces in the conflict -- 
as much as it is possible -- maximal restraint regarding 
activities and provocations, and finally, to do the utmost that 
can be done in the humanitarian field. I believe that UN 
helicopters will fly in in the morning to evacuate the wounded 
and killed. If we manage to implement the cease-fire and 
achieve a certain disengagement of forces, then we can say that 
we are drawing closer to peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  [Kusmuk] Addressing the assembled journalists, Akashi said: 
  [Akashi in English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian 
translation] President Karadzic and I agreed that a cease-fire 
around Gorazde should go into effect immediately and that troops 
would be withdrawn from the town as soon as possible. We agreed 
that all sides should maximally restrain themselves from all 
offensive activities. In the meantime we shall review the talks 
and try to sign an agreement as soon as possible in order to 
stabilize the situation. President Karadzic agreed to an urgent 
evacuation of humanitarian personnel and population from 
Gorazde. UNPROFOR is ready to do so tomorrow morning at 0800. 
  [Kusmuk] At around 1730 in the presidency of the Srpska 
republic, informal talks continued between diplomats and the 
political leadership of the republic. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

