<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Planes Chase Serb MiG-21 Over Travnik </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Planes Chase Serb MiG-21 Over Travnik </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1604212794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1604212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ahmet Begicevic for Bosnia-Herzegovina Radio and </F>
Television from Travnik] 
  [Text] A general alert was sounded in Travnik this evening 
because the aggressor fired several tank shells at the town from 
the foothills of Mount Vlasic. 
  A child was wounded by shrapnel and, at the same time, an 
artillery attack was launched on the first defense lines in 
Turbe, a Muslim-held town west of Travnik. 
  At dusk the inhabitants of Travnik witnessed how NATO 
aircraft chased after a Serb plane that had suddenly appeared in 
our country's airspace, flying at a low altitude. According to 
eye-witness accounts, it is most likely that this was a MiG-21 
plane which acrobatically fled toward Banja Luka in panic after 
the NATO planes appeared. Due to low clouds we are not able to 
inform you about the epilogue of this close air encounter, but 
we can say that the (?NATO) air force was active above central 
Bosnia for almost one hour, which is an unusually long period 
and is a sign that something indeed took place in the sky. 

</TEXT>

