<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Not Ready To Normalize UN Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Not Ready To Normalize UN Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504200694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1832 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 15 Apr (TANJUG) -- The supreme command of 
the armed forces of the Srpska republic met today in Pale, 
chaired by the supreme commander, Radovan Karadzic. 
  The participants reviewed the current military and political 
situation following the deployment of NATO aircraft on combat 
actions on the side of the Muslims. 
  It was noted that, by resorting to the use of air power and 
other means, certain circles in the West, the United States in 
particular, wish to goad the Srpska republic into concluding 
local and regional agreements and making other concessions. 
This particularly applies to the sectors of the front where the 
Muslims are in an unfavorable military situation and is geared 
toward encouraging the Muslims and creating conditions for 
attaining military and territorial objectives, a statement from 
the office of the president of the Srpska republic says. 
  The supreme command concludes that conditions are not yet 
ripe for the normalization of relations with UNPROFOR's [UN 
Protection Forces] military sector, but that the president of 
the Srpska republic may, if need be, and if he personally deems 
it necessary, maintain contact with UNPROFOR's civilian 
department with the aim of examining possibilities for extending 
the peace process, the statement reads. 

</TEXT>

