<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Free 19 UN Peacekeepers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Free 19 UN Peacekeepers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1704131994 Paris AFP in English 1300 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1704131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 17 (AFP) -- Serb forces Sunday [17 
April] released 19 UN peacekeepers who had been held hostage for 
three days at a barracks at Ilijas, north of here, a UN 
spokesman said in the Bosnian capital. 
  The peacekeepers were freed at 1:35 p.m. (1135 GMT), said 
Major Eric Chaperon. 
  The troops, 16 Canadian peacekeepers and three military 
observers of unspecified nationality, were due to return to 
their post at Cifluk, 19 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of 
Sarajevo, Chaperon said. 
  They had been deployed there to monitor seven Serb mortar 
and 
two anti-aircraft cannons. 
  The batteries had been retained in Cifluk in violation of 
the 
February accord under which Bosnian Serbs agreed to withdraw all 
heavy weapons from a 20-kilometre (12-mile) exclusion zone 
around the Bosnian capital under threat of North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation air strikes. 
  Bosnian Serb forces still detained or blocked Sunday 
hundreds 
of United Nations peacekeepers in several Serb-held sectors of 
Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

