<H3> <TI>   Gorazde Situation Worsens as Attack Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gorazde Situation Worsens as Attack Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Serbs Agree to International Buffer Force </H4>

<F P=102> AU1704140694 Paris AFP in English 1342 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1704140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 17 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs agreed 
Sunday to the deployment of a 336-member international buffer 
force in the Moslem enclave of Gorazde, UN spokesman Major Dacre 
Halloway said Sunday. 
  He said the agreement was reached earlier between UN special 
envoy Yasushi Akashi and Serb authorities meeting in nearby 
Pale, stronghold of Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic. 
  Under it, the multinational force -- more than half of whose 
members are French -- will be allowed to move around freely in 
Gorazde and helicopters will be able to fly to, in, and around 
the enclave, the spokesman said. 
  Deployment of the force was one of the conditions Akashi set 
earlier for resuming peace negotiations in Pale. 
  The force, composed of 170 Frenchmen, 66 Ukrainians, 50 
Egyptians and 50 British, has been on alert at Sarajevo airport 
since Friday, ready to leave within two hours' notice of the 
signing of an agreement. 
  The Ukrainian troops are to take up position on the hills 
overlooking Gorazde, to the southeast. 
  Halloway said the French would leave first for Gorazde, 
travelling by road, and would be escorted by Bosnian Serb forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8855 </DOCNO>
