<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose: Five UN Military Observers in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rose: Five UN Military Observers in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804151294 Paris AFP in English 1435 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1804151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 18 (AFP) -- The United Nations 
withdrew seven of its liaison officers from the besieged eastern 
Bosnian enclave of Gorazde Monday but left five unarmed military 
observers behind, General Michael Rose, the UN ground commander 
in Bosnia, said. 
  Rose said the liaison officers were pulled out of the Moslem 
enclave at dawn because their equipment was not usable. He did 
not elaborate on what he meant by that. 
  Earlier in Zagreb, a French military source reported that 
the 
UN had pulled all of its personnel from Gorazde overnight Sunday 
as the Serbs intensified their shelling of the town where some 
60,000 people are trapped. 
  The UN High Commissioner for Refugees in Geneva said four of 
its representatives also remain in the enclave. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

