<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Local Government Elections Scheduled for 19 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Local Government Elections Scheduled for 19 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804162794 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1415 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 18 Apr--On 18 April, the prime minister 
announced that the elections to parish councils would be held on 
19 June. The elections are to be held according to the old 
electoral law passed in 1990, Ewa Wachowicz, Prime Minister 
Waldemar Pawlak's press secretary, told PAP. 
  The prime minister has ordered that the elections be held 
without waiting for the president to make his decision--a few 
days ago the president announced that he would veto the new 
electoral law (passed by the Sejm on 18 March)--and without 
waiting for the Sejm, which can reject the president's veto by a 
majority of two-thirds of the votes. The president has until 21 
April to make his decision. 
  The most important difference between the two laws is the 
threshold where proportional representation applies. According 
to the old law, the threshold is 40,000 citizens, and, according 
to the new one, the threshold stands at 15,000 citizens. 

</TEXT>

