<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Meets Kinkel, Stresses Embargo Losses </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhelev Meets Kinkel, Stresses Embargo Losses </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504133794 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1300 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1504133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 15 April President Zhelev received Klaus Kinkel, 
German vice chancellor and minister of foreign affairs. 
Valentin Stoyanov, spokesman for the president, describes the 
character of the meeting: 
  [Begin Stoyanov recording] President Zhelev again stated 
that integration into European structures is a basic priority of 
Bulgarian foreign policy. He expressed the hope that Germany 
will facilitate the ratification of the agreement on Bulgaria's 
associated membership in the European Union. 
  Klaus Kinkel said that the ratification will probably take 
place before the elections. In addition he said he would do 
what he could to help increase German investments in Bulgaria. 
He pointed out, however, that this also depends on Bulgaria. 
We must become a more attractive country. 
  President Zhelev again stressed the losses Bulgaria is 
suffering from the Yugoslav embargo and pointed out that not 
only economic operations that have been affected, as the road to 
the West has been closed. Despite the fact that there are no 
military actions on Bulgarian territory, we are considered a 
risky state merely because we are located in the Balkans. This 
is something from which we will perhaps suffer even in the next 
few years. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

