<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman on Relations With Bosnia, Serbia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman on Relations With Bosnia, Serbia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804210194 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatia's President Franjo Tudjman today granted an 
interview to a British publicist, Sir Fitzroy McLean, to be 
broadcast on Dutch television, regarding affairs in southeastern 
Europe and the history of relations between nations in the 
former Yugoslavia. 
  Commenting on the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, President 
Tudjman stressed that, through the Washington agreement on the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina federation and its confederation with the 
Republic of Croatia, Croatian and Muslim interests have been 
harmonized with the interests of the Republic of Croatia and 
those of the Western world that wanted to link Muslims with 
Western civilization. 
  Speaking about relations between Croatia and Serbia, the 
Croatian president said that the mutual recognition will create 
the basis for peace and the establishment of a new international 
order in that part of Europe. He also said that the area of the 
Balkans should undergo a process of Scandinavization, recalling 
that the Scandinavian states recognized each other after years 
of being at war, then cooperated with each other, and 
successfully resolved the question of protecting minorities' 
rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

