<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Granic Meets With Redman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Granic Meets With Redman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804225694 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 2130 
GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804225694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic this evening 
received special UN envoy Charles Redman. Following the talks 
Charles Redman stated that the United States has very close and 
good cooperation with the Croatian Government: 
  [Begin Redman recording in English with superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] On this occasion I am staying in 
Croatia just very briefly, on my way from Sarajevo to 
Washington. Some very important decisions ought to be reached 
as regards what we can do in order to strengthen the UN role in 
Bosnia. 
  At the same time, nobody will forget that we ought to work 
on 
some very important issues here in Croatia. We have made 
significant progress, but we still need to do more, and I hope 
that my meeting and talks with Minister Granic will strengthen 
this process and achieve progress in the right direction. We 
are both pleased with the progress that has been achieved in the 
past months. On behalf of the United States, I would like to say 
that it is our intention to stay in close touch with the 
Croatian Government so that this process should proceed further. 
[end recording] 
  Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic said that one of the 
main issues discussed in talks with the special U.S. envoy was 
the current situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina: 
  [Begin Granic recording] We discussed the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, in particular [word indistinct] Gorazde, 
progress reached in talks between the Croats and the Bosniaks 
regarding setting up the federation of Bosnia-Herzegovina, and 
the situation in UN protected areas, the latest behaviur 
displayed by the Serbs in the UN protected areas and in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and the possible U.S. and UN moves. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

