<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kucan Admits Arms Supplied to Croatia, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kucan Admits Arms Supplied to Croatia, Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704130594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1039 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, April 17 (TANJUG) -- Slovenia's President 
Milan Kucan has admitted that Slovenia supplied arms to Croatia 
and Bosnian Moslems in defiance of a U.N. ban on arms deliveries 
to ex- Yugoslavia's territory. 
  In a letter to Slovenian Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek, 
carried by Ljubljana papers, Kucan demanded a government 
investigation into arms smuggling to determine who was involved, 
what was the profit of officials, institutions and individuals 
gained in that way, and the exact quantity of arms delivered to 
Slovenia from abroad. 
  The truth about Slovenia's involvement in arms smuggling 
came 
out in the public last summer, when 120 tonnes of weapons for 
Croatia and Bosnian Moslems were recovered at Maribor airport. 
  By drawing attention to arms smuggling, Kucan attempted to 
attenuate his role in the affair that assumed international 
proportions. 
  Kucan's "considerate" letter to Drnovsek is also intended to 
build up his reputation, but it will probably trigger new 
polemics instead, notably about the ex-Defence Minister Janez 
Jansa's role in Slovenia's instigating armed conflicts in former 
Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8902 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu076_s_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-076 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Interior Minister Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Interior Minister Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904182494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1729 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Maribor, April 19 (TANJUG) -- Slovenia's former 
Interior Minister Igor Bavcar has confirmed that well-organised 
channels had been delivering arms to Moslems in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina via Slovenia in spite of the embargo on arms 
exports to the entire territory of former Yugoslavia. 
  Speaking at a trial to the smugglers of 120 tons of arms 
discovered at the Maribor airport last summer, Bavcar said that 
the Slovenian Interior Ministry had sent to Slovenian border 
authorities permits for free passage of arms for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Slovenia's retired intelligence service number two man Janez 
Piber confirmed in court that Slovenian President Milan Kucan 
and Bavcar had introduced him to Hasan Cengic, who had been 
authorised by Bosnian Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic to obtain 
arms. 
  Piber said he had been told to assist Cengic even before the 
outbreak of armed conflicts in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

