<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Serbian Offensive Reported 19 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Serbian Offensive Reported 19 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Muslim Attacks Reported </H4>

<F P=102> LD1904193794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1848 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1904193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cajnice, 19 April (TANJUG) -- Positions of the army 
of the republic of Srpska on the left bank of the Drina river 
have since early this morning been exposed to fierce artillery 
fire coming from Muslim forces in the center of Gorazde, the 
command of the Herzegovina corps announced this evening. The 
attacks intensified after NATO aircraft had begun overflying 
Serb positions between Gorazde and Cajnice this afternoon. This 
encouraged Muslim forces to attempt to carry out infantry 
onslaughts in several places along the separation line. 
  The command of the Herzegovina corps said that for their 
attacks, Muslim forces have been using facilities in which 
representatives of international humanitarian organizations and 
the UN are accommodated. Fire from anti-aircraft guns and 
machine-guns has been opened from the hospital building, 
schools, and other institutions. 
  The command of the Herzegovina corps today resolutely denied 
reports broadcast by Sarajevo media that the Serb army used 
chemical weapons, stressing that this has been done by Muslim 
forces which have a factory for the production of the banned 
chemicals in Gorazde. Despite the fierce attacks, the Serb 
forces today managed to preserve their front lines, the command 
said. 

</TEXT>

