<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG: U.S. `Spurred' on by Churkin Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    TANJUG: U.S. `Spurred' on by Churkin Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904182694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1811 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 19 (TANJUG) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton and members of the National Security Council on Tuesday 
morning [19 April] began discussions on a future U.S. diplomatic 
and military platform for Bosnia-Herzegovina. As indicated by 
U.S. Administration officials, the basic U.S. idea is to try to 
persuade its allies and the United Nations to step up air 
attacks on Bosnian serb targets. Yesterday's verbal attack on 
the Bosnian Serb leadership by Vitaliy Churkin in Moscow has 
directly spurred and encouraged Clinton's advisors to opt for 
more severe punitive measures against the Bosnian Serbs, sources 
in Washington said. 
  Churkin's statement that Russia would not allow the Serbs to 
treat it as a `banana republic' and that `negotiations with the 
Serbs' should be suspended was received in the White House with 
relief because it was interpreted as a direct suggestion to the 
U.S. to adopt a radical platform which would not be countered by 
a Russian veto. 
  Commenting on Churkin's statement, Russian Ambassador to the 
United Nations Yuriy Vorontsov said that neither the Russian 
Government nor President Boris Yeltsin were behind it. U.S. 
papers write that Monday's request by U.N. Secretary-General 
Butros Butros-Ghali for new NATO actions against Bosnian Serbs 
had been inspired by U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations 
Madeleine Albright, who is also a member of the National 
Security Council. On Monday, she was briefly absent from a 
National Security Council session, which discussed proposals for 
Tuesday's meeting with Clinton, in order to telephone to 
Butros-Ghali and tell him that the White House was willing to 
launch more radical air strikes on the Bosnian Serbs. 
  Observers in Washington are not sure what kind of reception 
the new, more radical U.S. variant will get. It is believed 
that a difficult diplomatic manoeuvre will be needed to win over 
NATO allies for a wider-scale bombing. Indicating a tougher 
stand toward the Bosnian Serbs, U.S. papers and a part of 
political structures on Tuesday said that the White House was 
ready to exempt the Bosnian Moslems from the embargo on arms 
deliveries to all sides in former Yugoslavia. After an 
incredible pressure from the Congress and the radical wing in 
the White House on Monday, the issue was put on the agenda of 
Clinton's meeting with the National Security Council on Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8920 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu076_i_94020" </HT>


