<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim-Croat Skirmishes Reported in Gornji Vakuf </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslim-Croat Skirmishes Reported in Gornji Vakuf </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004010794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2241 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004010794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Srbobran, April 19 (TANJUG) -- The separation of 
Moslem and Croat forces in the area of Gornji Vakuf and the 
division of the territory of this town in central 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, which began on Tuesday [19 April], are 
accompanied by frequent incidents and exchange of fire between 
the two armies, Bosnian Serb military sources said. 
  Moslems will keep the name Gornji Vakuf for their part of 
the 
town, while the Croats will change the name to Uskoplje. Gornji 
Vakuf will be the third town that has been carved up by the 
Moslems and Croats. Mostar, the biggest town and the 
administrative seat of the region of Herzegovina in the 
southwest of the republic, and Vitez, in the central part, have 
already been divided. These towns were the sites of the 
heaviest one-year Moslem-Croat clashes in the central and 
southern parts of Bosnia-Herzegovina when they were fighting for 
territories. 
  The ceasefire agreement and division of territories followed 
the signing of an agreement on a Moslem-Croat federation in 
Washington on March 18 under strong U.S. pressure. The 
federation should eventually form a confederation with 
neighbouring Croatia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

