<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Reacts to CNN Complaint on License </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Reacts to CNN Complaint on License </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004142294 </F>
<F P=103> AU2004142294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Bratislava SMENA in Slovak on 16 April 
on page 12 carries a 200-word TA SR report entitled "CNN 
Protests." The report states that the U.S. Cable News Network 
(CNN) company, which is one of the applicants for a license to 
broadcast on the STV (Slovak Television) 2 channel, which is to 
be partly privatized, "accused Slovak legislators of 
discriminating against foreign companies in the competition for 
a license to broadcast on the second Slovak Television channel." 
Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak on 18 April on page 1, under the 
headline "Discrimination in the Law on Tenders?," carries a 
200-word TA SR report on Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik's 
response to the CNN complaint. 
  According to the Bratislava SMENA report, in a letter 
addressed to the Slovak parliament, the prime minister, and the 
president, CNN said that, "by setting four new conditions for 
license applicants, Slovakia has signaled that it is not 
interested in foreign capital" and charged that "the approach by 
the Slovak Council for Radio and Television Broadcasting 
discourages foreign investors and suggests that they are not 
welcome here." The CNN letter was referring to new 
requirements, under which foreign stake in the license holder's 
company must not exceed 45 percent and under which the license 
holder must reserve 50 percent of broadcasting time for European 
productions. 
  The Bratislava PRAVDA report on Prime Minister Moravcik's 
reaction states that "the Government of the Slovak Republic is 
greatly interested in the observance of general customs, which 
are also laid down in our legal system, concerning competitions 
and public tenders. It is from this point of view that we will 
assess the whole matter surrounding the report on the CNN 
letter." Moravcik announces that the government will "assume an 
official standpoint" after it has familiarized itself with "the 
whole case." 

</TEXT>

