<H3> <TI>   Belgrade Allows Transit of UNPROFOR Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Belgrade Allows Transit of UNPROFOR Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1904222094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2210 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1904222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 19 (TANJUG) -- The government of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia on Tuesday [19 April] approved a 
request of the U.N. Protection Force [UNPROFOR] for transit 
through Yugoslav territory for the Ukrainian and Russian 
batallions which are to join UNPROFOR in Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
Federal Information Ministry said today in Belgrade. There are 
already 550 Ukrainian troops on the UNPROFOR in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and 160 more left Ukraine for that former 
Yugoslav Republic on Monday. The first 100 soldiers of the 
additional Russian UNPROFOR contingent left Russia in late March 
and are already in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Most of them have been 
deployed in the area of Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

