<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Djonovic Notes Need To Import Food </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Djonovic Notes Need To Import Food </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804114594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1127 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804114594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 18 (TANJUG) -- Two years of economic 
sanctions have made it necessary for Yugoslavia to import food 
articles it used to export to meet the most basic needs of its 
population, experts of Serbia's Ministry of Agriculture set out. 
Despite great potential in food production, Yugoslavia would 
have to import some 100,000 tonnes of sugar, some 400 million 
liters of milk, 50,000 tonnes of potatoes and 20,000 tones of 
beans, said Ivko Djonovic, Serbian agriculture minister in an 
interview to Belgrade's daily BORBA Monday. 
  In this way, Djonovic denied assessments by federal 
government experts that farmers would this year secure enough 
food to satisfy the needs of the Yugoslav population. Yugoslav 
farmers have prior to the introduction of the sanctions exported 
all currently deficient articles. Thus, Yugoslav sugar 
factories earned 300 million dollars annually from sugar 
exports, said Djonovic. 
  Market surpluses, in his view, could be expected in basic 
cultures such as grain and maize. Experts assessed that some 
2.5 million tonnes of grain would this year be reaped in Serbia. 
Yugoslavia's overall needs may be met with 1.5 million tonnes. 
  Apart from its population of 10.4 million, more than 500,000 
officially registered refugees from the former Yugoslav 
republics, were a cause for concern. 

</TEXT>

