<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clampdown on Independent Media Feared </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clampdown on Independent Media Feared </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004055394 Belgrade BORBA in Serbo-Croatian 19 Apr 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> AU2004055394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade BORBA </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Prelude to a Clash With Domestic </F>
Journalists"] 
  [Text] Belgrade -- "The statement by Milorad Vucelic, 
prominent socialist and director general of the Serbian Radio 
and Television, to Novi Sad DNEVNIK that the purge of foreign 
journalists is fully justified, sheds considerably more light on 
the real essence of the latest democratic initiative by the 
Serbian authorities." This was stated in a communique issued by 
the UGS [Association of City Trade Unions] "Independence". "We 
thought that this was only interference in the editorial policy 
of other papers, but thanks to the aforementioned statement, it 
is now becoming clear that this move has far reaching 
consequences in the internal political arena. 
  The pogrom of foreign journalists is only warming up, a 
prelude to the final showdown with those who do not share the 
same views at home. By throwing foreigners out, Serbia is only 
making sure that there will be no easing or lifting of the 
sanctions so that, in the total darkness and without witnesses, 
it can finish off the independent media and independent 
journalists devoted to their profession, "Independence" claims. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8949 </DOCNO>
