<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Declare Peace `Unilaterally' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Declare Peace `Unilaterally' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004115094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1125 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 20 Apr (TANJUG) -- The office of Radovan 
Karadzic, president of the republic of Srpska, announced today 
that "the Serbian side has declared peace in Gorazde 
unilaterally, thus ending the crisis surrounding this town," 
SRNA has reported. "Under an agreement between the republic of 
Srpska authorities and the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR], a 
cease-fire on the Gorazde front comes into force immediately and 
UN troops will be able to enter Gorazde today. This will help 
the international humanitarian organizations to resume their 
work in the town," the statement says. 
  It is noted in the statement that the Serbian side's 
unilateral move is a republic of Srpska response to yesterday's 
declaration by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and the position 
of U.S. President Bill Clinton on the crisis in Gorazde. "We 
appeal to the international community to put pressure on the 
Muslim side to make possible a resumption of the peace 
negotiations," the statement says, adding that the time has come 
for the Muslims to state clearly if they favor war or peace. 
  "The Muslim strategy of maintaining a state of neither war 
nor peace is a crime," the statement stresses and reminds the 
international community that the Serbs did not start the 
conflict in Gorazde, that they want a just agreement, but will 
not allow themselves to be dictated to. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8991 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu076_i_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-076 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

