<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Deployment Authorized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Deployment Authorized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004070794 Paris AFP in English 0102 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2004070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 20 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic early Wednesday [20 April] authorised the 
deployment of 100 UN troops in the beleagured Moslem enclave of 
Gorazde, Bosnian Serb radio said. The UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) "can from Wednesday morning deploy 100 soldiers in 
the part of the town situated on the left bank of the Drina" 
river, Karadzic announced. The authorisation came as part of a 
third ceasefire the Serb leader has negotiated with UN 
representatives in as many days. 
  The details of the agreement remain to be discussed with the 
United Nations special envoy to the former Yugoslavia Yasushi 
Akashi, the radio quoted him as saying. Akashi has come under 
criticism from Bosnian Moslems after holding fruitless talks 
with Karadzic Sunday as Serb tanks poured into Gorazde, giving 
the Serbs virtual control of the town. 
  Karadzic said Wednesday that UN soldiers would be allowed to 
"protect the civilian population but not the Bosnian Army," Serb 
radio reported. "The aim of the Serb counter-offensive is not 
to take the town but only the right bank of the Drina which 
belongs to the Serbs," the Serb leader added. But relations 
between the Serbs and the military wing of the UN mission in 
Bosnia would remain suspended "because of the active role it is 
playing in the civil war." Reponsibility for the fighting 
around Gorazde rests with the United Nations, as "it has not 
disarmed the Moslem (Bosnian) army in a region that was supposed 
to be demilitarised," Karadzic argued. 
  The radio made no mention of the release by Bosnian Serb 
forces Tuesday of six out of eight teams of UN military 
observers that they had detained last week in retaliation for 
NATO airstrikes around Gorazde. The teams, comprising three to 
five people, were reported by the UN Tuesday to have been been 
freed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

