<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Germany's Kinkel Arrives, Promises Help </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Germany's Kinkel Arrives, Promises Help </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504103094 Sofia BTA in English 0954 GMT 15 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1504103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 15 (BTA) -- Arriving on an official 
visit here last night, today Germany's Vice Chancellor and 
Minister for Foreign Affairs Klaus Kinkel had talks with 
Bulgarian Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov. They considered 
bilateral relations and a range of international problems. Mr. 
Kinkel familiarized Mr. Daskalov with the European Union's 
efforts to put an end to the conflict in the former Yugoslavia. 
They also discussed the situation in Russia and 
Bulgarian-Russian relations. 
  "I had the opportunity to emphasize the importance we attach 
to Bulgaria and our willingness to help it solve its problems, 
ensuing mainly from the disintegration of the ex-Soviet market 
and the Yugo-embargo, "Mr. Kinkel told the media later. The 
sides discussed Bulgaria's foreign debt, a problem which Mr. 
Kinkel believes has been recently settled. Mr. Kinkel and Mr. 
Daskalov made a review of Bulgaria's relations with a number of 
international organizations, such as the European Union, the 
Western European Union, the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade organization, NATO, and the Organization for Economic 
Cooperation and Development, and its desire to get integrated 
with them. "Bulgaria can rely on Germany's support in this 
respect," Minister Kinkel stressed. "Klaus Kinkel's message is 
that Germany has supported Bulgaria and always will but, 
naturally, to become more attractive we should accelerate the 
reform," the Bulgarian foreign minister said after the meeting. 
  "Our bilateral relations are not purely bilateral because 
they are maintained through the European Union in part," Foreign 
Minister Stanislav Daskalov said. 
  At the talks with his German counterpart, Minister Daskalov 
raised the visa problem. Bulgaria expects that Germany will 
relax its visa regulations. However, the Bulgarian foreign 
minister told the media that this was a delicate issue and 
resolving it would take time. 
  The Bulgarian side raised the question of considering the 
possibilities for more active German investments in Bulgaria. 
It requested assistance for the promotion of relations with the 
organization which would succeed Cocom [Coordinating Committee 
for Multilateral Export Controls] and for the allocation of more 
funds to Bulgaria within the framework of the Operation PHARE 
[Economic and Reconstruction Aid for Poland and Hungary] 
Programme. Asked what the German side insisted on, Minister 
Daskalov said that it requested "to continue reforms in Bulgaria 
despite the difficulties and pursue a foreign policy that will 
create no problems." 
  "Bulgaria's debt to the former German Democratic Republic 
has 
not been discussed," Minister Daskalov said in reply to a 
reporter's question. "Experts will continue, on a bilateral 
basis, the talks opened in 1991 and I hope that we will be able 
to find some compromising solution to the problem," Mr. Daskalov 
said. Bulgaria is indebted to the former GDR, but the German 
side has unilaterally cancelled a number of transactions 
concluded with this country. Describing the dispute as quite 
serious, he said that both Bulgaria and Germany should show 
flexibility. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
